1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Good morning. It's June 20th, 2014. My name is David Cline and I'm here in Chester, Virginia, on behalf of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture, to interview the Reverend Dr. Rev. Dr. Wyatt Tee Walker.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Neglected to say thank you very much for meeting with us this morning and it's quite an honor for me personally.

4
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Appreciate the memories. My name is Rev. Dr. Wyatt Tee Walker. I was born in Brockton, Massachusetts, August 16, 1928.

5
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
And my only claim to fame is that I was once chief of staff at Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.

6
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:02,000
That's quite a claim to fame. If I may, I'm always interested in how people's backgrounds influence the way their lives later played out.

7
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:06,000
So could you tell us a little bit about your family and growing up?

8
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Well I grew up as a preacher's kid. My father was a congregation in South Jersey of about a hundred small church.

9
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:24,000
He was a very scholarly gentleman. He read Greek and Hebrew every day.

10
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:34,000
And his style of ministry, I'm sure, influenced me and my work as a pastor.

11
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:43,000
And he was *not* too keen about me joining Martin King and leaving the church I was serving at Petersburg at the time.

12
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:47,000
But he came to appreciate a great deal.

13
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Could you tell us a little bit about how you did it?

14
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Yes, I'm doing a go.

15
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,000
Okay, I got it.

16
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:03,000
Did you have any early encounters with racism or segregation in New Jersey?

17
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:07,000
I lost my first girlfriend because of it.

18
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:13,000
It was a little girl who lived within two blocks from my home, named Nancy.

19
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:17,000
And we used to play together.

20
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:23,000
And one day she came to the curb from her house and she was sort of crying.

21
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,000
And she said she couldn't play with me anymore.

22
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:30,000
I said why? She said because you're colored.

23
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:33,000
I didn't even know what that meant.

24
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:36,000
But later I understood it.

25
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:42,000
And my first schooling was segregated schools.

26
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:51,000
And my first experience of integration in education was in junior high school and high school.

27
00:02:51,000 --> 00:03:03,000
And so, and in town that I lived in, it was a drug store and you couldn't be served in it.

28
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:08,000
And Ku Klux Klan was operative in area.

29
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:16,000
they burned a cross on one of the father's divine headquarters.

30
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:23,000
*It* was like growing up in the south, really.

31
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:30,000
But I couldn't compare it until later on in life.

32
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:35,000
So, and my father was a race man.

33
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:45,000
And he was always involved in trying to find some reconciliation between the white and the black community.

34
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:56,000
And I grew up with a portrait of Frederick Douglass on the wall.

35
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:04,000
And so, I was very familiar with the history of our people in America.

36
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:14,000
And I resented everything about the segregation pattern that existed.

37
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:27,000
I guess, widely, but in the section of North South Jersey we lived in and we called it Little Georgia because it was so bad.

38
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:34,000
And did you, when you were called to the church, did you initially think that the church might be a way for you to address these issues?

39
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Initially, in fact, when I finished university I was a major in physics and chemistry.

40
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:48,000
And I wanted to be a physician.

41
00:04:48,000 --> 00:05:01,000
But the call to the ministry seemed to be more pressing because of my experiences in Richmond, Virginia with segregation and discrimination.

42
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:13,000
And I saw that as the best means of fighting segregation in any form that I found it.

43
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:26,000
the Black preacher is the freest man in society because he is accountable to the black community.

44
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:33,000
And I could, I had discerned that in my early college experience.

45
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:39,000
And what kinds of things did you involve your congregation and early on in terms of?

46
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:45,000
Well, it was more active when I was a pastor in the Harlem.

47
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:58,000
We were against the drug traffic and we pick it in and demonstrate march against drug enterprises.

48
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:11,000
So I guess my interest focused on seniors, the drug traffic and working to develop affordable housing.

49
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:24,000
And at the point that I left New York, I had become the largest developer of affordable housing in New York State.

50
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,000
So that's a part of the legacy of my service.

51
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:32,000
It's wonderful. We'll get to that story in a little bit.

52
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:38,000
If I could focus just for a second on Richmond and your first pastor in New York.

53
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:49,000
Well, I went to the undergraduate school of Virginia Union University and then I went to the graduate school of religion to earn my MDiv.

54
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:58,000
And I was called to a church in Petersburg in my last year.

55
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:07,000
I was 22 years old. I thought I really found out recently that I was 23.

56
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:18,000
I had always used my birth year as 29 and visiting a sister who was recovering from a automobile accident.

57
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:26,000
She had my mother's papers among which was my birth certificate and my birth date was 1928.

58
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:35,000
So instead of me looking forward to my 86 birthday, I'm looking forward to my 87th and all because this year.

59
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:41,000
So in after Petersburg?

60
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:49,000
Well, I was in Petersburg eight years as a pastor at the Gillfield Baptist Church which is over 200 years old.

61
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,000
And I went to New York and joined the corporate world.

62
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:58,000
I was in a publishing firm. I was a marketing director.

63
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:08,000
And then I went to I was called to a church in Harlem and I served there for 37 years.

64
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:17,000
And it was a wonderful ministry and the way I responded to my leadership.

65
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:22,000
Can I ask you about an early incident with a library?

66
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
Was that here in Richmond?

67
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:28,000
Yes, in Petersburg. Can you tell us a little bit about that?

68
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:36,000
Yes. Of course, everything was segregated in Petersburg when I arrived, including the ministerial alliance.

69
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:47,000
And the first experience I had in integrating was integrating it with the Chaplain of Virginia State.

70
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:54,000
And another pastor in the town, RG Williams.

71
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:59,000
We integrated the ministerial alliance.

72
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:13,000
And about eight years later, I tried to get the city council to integrate the library and they would not even consider it.

73
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:21,000
And for some reason, the N. W. C. would not make a case of it.

74
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
And I felt they had pulled a rug from under me.

75
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:30,000
So I influenced the gang by King.

76
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,000
I had a demonstration.

77
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:39,000
And we went there on February 27th, 1960.

78
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:47,000
And we went through the white door, which we were promptly arrested in a few minutes.

79
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:53,000
And two of us, (Rev.) R.G. Williams + I (Walker), the two of us decided to stay in jail.

80
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
We stayed in jail a couple of days.

81
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:00,000
And of course, that was back in that day.

82
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:03,000
That was big news.

83
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:12,000
And unusual because the black community in Petersburg had been so cowed by the system of segregation.

84
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:18,000
They wouldn't even think of trying to integrate a facility.

85
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:26,000
And it happened that it was the first time the library had been desegregated in the South.

86
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:28,000
Do you remember what book it was that you...

87
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Yes, I do.

88
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:38,000
I asked for a volume one of Douglas Elvall Freeman's biography of Robert E. Lee.

89
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:43,000
I always thought Lee was guilty of treason.

90
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:50,000
And I just thought I'd look at this book to see what the Southern view was.

91
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
Why they made him such a hero.

92
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:57,000
Did anybody comment on the fact that you would check out Lee's biography?

93
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:07,000
I've seen several articles about it, the how I asked ironically for that book.

94
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:12,000
And that led to my arrest.

95
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:18,000
And did you already know Dr. King at that point?

96
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:20,000
Or at what point did you get to know him?

97
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:26,000
In 19...

98
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:31,000
It must have been 1952.

99
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:36,000
And I joined his organization and he put me on the board.

100
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:44,000
And I did some writing for him in press releases because I had that set of skills.

101
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
And so I've been close to him since 1952 until his death.

102
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:54,000
In fact, the day before he was assassinated, he had called my home.

103
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
And wanted to talk to me about something.

104
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,000
I don't know why.

105
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:11,000
I have always imagined that he wanted me to come to Memphis to help with the march that had gone wrong the day before.

106
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:17,000
But you know, I just don't know.

107
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:22,000
But he had a great influence on my life.

108
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:29,000
When I went to Petersburg as a pastor, I carried a Smith & Wesson nickel-plated .32.

109
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:33,000
And Martin Luther King's influence, I put my gun down.

110
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:40,000
I was waiting for some racist to cross my path.

111
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:45,000
And I had in my mind that I had *his (father's) pistol, [to] shoot him*.

112
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:56,000
And I got that idea from my father who was in a train station somewhere near Norfolk, Virginia.

113
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:02,000
And it was cold and he went in the so-called weight waiting room.

114
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:07,000
And the constable came in there and told him he had to leave.

115
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:10,000
The father told him he was too cold.

116
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:15,000
And the constable raised his hand.

117
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:18,000
His night stick to hitting.

118
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:23,000
My father said he had his coat on and his trigger on the gun.

119
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:27,000
And he said, *by the time it* started down.

120
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:29,000
He was going to shoot him.

121
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:35,000
And so from the very beginning, my father's early life to my early life.

122
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:40,000
That's why I say I know he was a race man.

123
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:44,000
And I'm sure I inherited some of that.

124
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:48,000
So was the concept of non-violence and practicing non-violence?

125
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:50,000
No, it wasn't in Vogue at that time.

126
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:54,000
So did that take some training and get him used to that idea for you?

127
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:01,000
Well, I took a lot of reading and hearing King over and over again.

128
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:10,000
Seeing his commitment to non-violence made me adopted it as a way of life.

129
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:21,000
But all through college, I envisioned putting together some smart young black man

130
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:30,000
who developed the expertise in using plastic bombs

131
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:41,000
and putting, I speak through the opponent's ears like (Theodore) Bilbo and (James) Eastland.

132
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:47,000
And that was what I fantasized during my college years.

133
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:55,000
And then I end up as Dr. King's right hand man in non-violence.

134
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:59,000
So life has its quirks and turns.

135
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:13,000
So you began working on the board when were you first called to actually join the organization?

136
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:21,000
Well, he invited me to the initial meeting in Atlanta, but I didn't have enough money to go.

137
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:36,000
And so I didn't join the SCLC until the meeting in Clarksdale, Mississippi in 1958, I think it was.

138
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:45,000
And that's when he put me on the board and I began to work close to him until his death.

139
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:52,000
And when you came on as a staff member, that was 1960.

140
00:15:52,000 --> 00:16:01,000
He invited me to *become* Executive Director of the organization to help build it

141
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:14,000
into what became the, in my view, the most powerful civil rights organization in the 60s.

142
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:16,000
You came in after Ella Baker?

143
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:17,000
Oh, absolutely.

144
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:18,000
Yes.

145
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:26,000
She was the interim executive director, but I was after her.

146
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:38,000
I knew her from an earlier experience, but that was after the fact.

147
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And what was the situation with the organization when you first arrived?

148
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:47,000
And how did you manage to grow it over?

149
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:56,000
Well, it was, I used to describe it as mainly an idea in Dr. King's briefcase.

150
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:07,000
And trying to connect churches and passages of former Rubo Task.

151
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:14,000
And I just, I flew by and just see to my parents as they say.

152
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:17,000
And I put a fundraising system in.

153
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:21,000
The budget, my first year was $57,000.

154
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:24,000
We did over 100,000.

155
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:32,000
And in four years, when I went, I took two members with me from my staff in Petersburg.

156
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:38,000
And that made SCLC a five staff member because they were two working here.

157
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:48,000
And when four years later, we had a budget of $1,000,000 and a hundred full-time employees.

158
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:55,000
So I worked primarily as administrator and a fund raiser.

159
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:07,000
And there were some way stations along the way, but things didn't really start popping until Albany and Birmingham.

160
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:10,000
Before we get to Albany, I just want to ask you talking about money.

161
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:13,000
How important was money to the success of the company?

162
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:16,000
It is the ammunition.

163
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:25,000
But you know, it takes money to run an organization and to run campaigns and to train people.

164
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:36,000
And that's what we needed the money for because non-advance was an altogether novel concept in 1960 and in 1961.

165
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:46,000
And we developed it into a driving force which changed the nation in a way.

166
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:51,000
It was responsible for desegregating America.

167
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:56,000
Of course, the movement in the streets has received to be really driving this change.

168
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:59,000
And it's a huge part of it, but there's so much going on behind this.

169
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:00,000
Oh, absolutely.

170
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:11,000
And there were so many pundits who thought that we just decided to go to a place and have some demonstration, by the way.

171
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:22,000
We started a year ahead of time in Birmingham and that's an illustration of what it takes to do to have great movements.

172
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:26,000
We were talking just about to talk about Albany, Georgia.

173
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:33,000
And if you could tell us a little bit about the invitation to come to Albany and the situation that you found there.

174
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:40,000
And then I'll ask you a little bit afterwards how that led to your tactics in Birmingham.

175
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:52,000
Well, Albany was considered by the media and the pundits who observed what was going on that it was a failure.

176
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:57,000
But in my view, it was a success.

177
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:02,000
We just made some mistakes.

178
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:07,000
In Albany, we shouldn't have, but we did make them.

179
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:13,000
But we were just beginning social revolution, so that's understandable.

180
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:16,000
The problem in Albany was twofold.

181
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:19,000
One, they had too many targets.

182
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:26,000
It was initiated by the workers, the SNCC workers, and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee.

183
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:37,000
And that resulted in the community being exhausted for fundraising and rallies, et cetera.

184
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:46,000
And SNCC realized that they were in over their heads and so they invited Dr. King to come.

185
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:51,000
Well, when King goes, I went.

186
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:56,000
And I had the reputation of running the tight ship.

187
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:05,000
And I reacted very defensively when they eliminated Dr. King to one vote.

188
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:12,000
And whatever the vote was, contrary to his advice, I thought was a mistake.

189
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:28,000
So there was some interesting warfare between the organizations, the core people, the NAACP, the local community organization, and the other Christian leadership conference.

190
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:37,000
And Louis Lomax, who never went to Albany, was African American journalists.

191
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:49,000
I said, Dr. King left Albany with his tail between his legs, you know, some remarkable, it was a failure.

192
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:52,000
And Louis Lomax never came to Albany.

193
00:21:52,000 --> 00:22:00,000
Only there was telephone interviews with students from SNCC.

194
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:03,000
And of course, they had a whole new view.

195
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:08,000
The organizational competition was very sharp.

196
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:23,000
And that's what caused the Albany power structure to be intransigent because they knew of this problem that we have with each other.

197
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:30,000
And as I said before, the other thing was they had too many targets.

198
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:44,000
But when we left Albany, everything was closed, the parks, the library, it wasn't like a Mexican standoff.

199
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:54,000
But in the process, the significance of Albany is that we learned how to mobilize an entire community for a campaign.

200
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:03,000
And if it had not been for Albany, and the experience we had there, we would not have won the Birmingham campaign.

201
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:08,000
So to me, that is chief significance.

202
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:13,000
I'm going to ask you just in a second the lessons and how you applied to Birmingham.

203
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:19,000
But I want to ask about a specific person there during the Albany campaign.

204
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:24,000
And that's Charles Melvin Sherrod, who was with SNCC, who you knew well.

205
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:30,000
Yes, in fact, I raised him in my congregation in Petersburg.

206
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:38,000
And got a Woolworth grant to help finance his education.

207
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:41,000
So I knew Sherrod very well.

208
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:45,000
At times he had been to my home and stayed.

209
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:53,000
So another one of those ironies of struggle.

210
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:56,000
Now there's a story that Sherrod told.

211
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:05,000
I don't know if you recall this incident, but I always loved this story that apparently in Albany at some point in a meeting with Robert Kennedy.

212
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:10,000
And Kennedy was saying he didn't want to see any more direct action when this voter registration.

213
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:17,000
And Sherrod got so angry, this is Sherrod telling this story, that he got so angry he wanted to take a swing.

214
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:21,000
He almost took a swing at the Attorney General and he held it back.

215
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:25,000
And I remember that meeting that was in Washington DC.

216
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:34,000
Kennedy administration always telling us to put our energy into voter registration.

217
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:39,000
And it was doom for failure if we did.

218
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:49,000
It was the protest marches in the action that made our movement what it was.

219
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:59,000
the obstacles to Black folks voting *were* huge.

220
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:05,000
the right to vote was theoretical *at* best.

221
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:11,000
Okay, so after Albany and Sites are said on Birmingham, you say you've learned some lessons from Albany.

222
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:14,000
What were this? So how did you plan for it?

223
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:24,000
The *main* lesson was how to organize the entire community for a campaign.

224
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:41,000
And in Albany we had sections of the city that we worked in developing and removed the mass means around from place to place in order to publicize what we were doing.

225
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:52,000
In Birmingham, the first week of the demonstrations there, the bus company went on strike.

226
00:25:52,000 --> 00:26:00,000
But we held mass meetings every night in some community for 43 nights.

227
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:05,000
It was just amazing what we were able to do when I looked back at it.

228
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:10,000
But that was the strength that we had.

229
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:17,000
And we had learned those lessons in Albany more than any place else.

230
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:22,000
Now you had become a convert to non-violent strategy at this point.

231
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:23,000
Oh yes.

232
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:27,000
But you were fond of this word confrontation.

233
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:29,000
So non-violent...

234
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:31,000
Oh, projects say yes.

235
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:36,000
Can you tell me a little bit about the necessity for confrontation?

236
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:44,000
Well, Dr. King assigned me to the task of working at a campaign strategy for Birmingham.

237
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:47,000
I went to Birmingham a year ahead of time.

238
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:58,000
And I went to the stores and I measured how long it would take a young person, a middle-aged person,

239
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:01,000
a middle-aged person to go to the stores.

240
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:05,000
How many seats were available in the eating facility?

241
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:09,000
So I was very detailed in that.

242
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:12,000
And that's how Project C grew.

243
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:20,000
And when I presented that to the executive committee of SCLC, it was unanimous.

244
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:23,000
The name was accepted.

245
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:30,000
And Project C was the heart of the campaign in Birmingham.

246
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:43,000
And led to the desegregation of America with the Public Accommodations title.

247
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:46,000
And just for clarification, Project C was the blueprint.

248
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:49,000
Can you say what that stands for and what the plan was?

249
00:27:49,000 --> 00:28:05,000
The Project C confrontation that we had to confront the evil that we discerned in the segregation system.

250
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:16,000
And the only way we could join it and we had in the back of our minds that Bull Connor would do something that would help us.

251
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:19,000
And he did.

252
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:26,000
He reacted in his way to our demonstrations.

253
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:37,000
And if he had meant for Bull Connor, we wouldn't have had the TV pictures that saturated America and foreign countries.

254
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:44,000
And force the business community decided we better talk.

255
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:47,000
So Bull Connor played right into the story.

256
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:50,000
He played it to a hands.

257
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:56,000
For some reason he had this idea that we should not be able to go downtown.

258
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:10,000
And if he had let us go on the first or second march or the third march, after about three or four marches downtown to Bray, what else was new?

259
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:16,000
It was his resistance to that which made the movement.

260
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:26,000
And got us sympathy from all quarters of the nation.

261
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:29,000
What about the children's movement part of that?

262
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:37,000
Well, the nonviolent credo dictates that anybody can be in the movement.

263
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:43,000
The Al Al Hibbler was arrested in Birmingham.

264
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:47,000
And so we didn't have any qualms that Dr. King and I didn't.

265
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:52,000
And James Bevel and we decided we'd use the children.

266
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:56,000
We knew there would be criticism about it.

267
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:08,000
But the children's march is what toppled the segregation system in Birmingham.

268
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:19,000
When people saw the firemen with the [fire] hoses using them against children running them down the sidewalk,

269
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:25,000
they said this won't do.

270
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:35,000
A physician in Mississippi told his son who was my new testament instructor at United Theological Seminary, that was [United Theological Seminary in] Dayton.

271
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:37,000
He said segregation is over.

272
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:40,000
And he was very prophetic in that.

273
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:46,000
And astonishing[ly], because people just didn't see.

274
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:51,000
They wouldn't accept treating children that way.

275
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:53,000
And the power of those images.

276
00:30:53,000 --> 00:31:00,000
How did you develop a sense of how these using the media in such a way to help your colleagues?

277
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:04,000
We did that with great premeditation.

278
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:09,000
We wanted to get on three or four minutes on a *Huntley-Brinkley* report.

279
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:15,000
And so we, I guess I was responsible.

280
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:20,000
I told Dr. King when he said to me,

281
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:28,000
you got to find some way to dramatize our situation.

282
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:32,000
And we were late with one of our demonstrations.

283
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And instead of marching at two, they marched at four.

284
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:43,000
By that time, a thousand people had gathered to expect something to happen.

285
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:55,000
And it was a lot of the energies with the onlookers, not participants in the struggle.

286
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:59,000
And I called the Lennon, I told him, I got it.

287
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:04,000
I said, I got it. I know what to do.

288
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:08,000
I said, I can't tell you on the phone when I got back to Atlanta.

289
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:12,000
I told him we had to slow down our demonstrations.

290
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:16,000
And so people came home and we were working together.

291
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:21,000
And Bull Connor would do something silly, which is what he did.

292
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:27,000
And put the dogs on us and use the water hoses.

293
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:32,000
We were then, I felt we were home free.

294
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:39,000
Because we *made the Huntley-Brinkley* report about two or three nights in a row.

295
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:46,000
And that was a key to the success of Birmingham, the use of the media.

296
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:52,000
Going back to the finances for a second, would you see an increase in fundraising after?

297
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:57,000
Absolutely, without a doubt.

298
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:04,000
I'm trying to think of the figures now, but they escaped me now.

299
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:15,000
But Birmingham put us, the Southern Christian East of Congress, on the map.

300
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:18,000
You knew about the NAACP.

301
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:22,000
They were outlawed in Alabama, so they couldn't operate.

302
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:27,000
And they didn't have action program.

303
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:31,000
They were not given to the demonstrations.

304
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:35,000
They were fighting the battle through courts.

305
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:43,000
And to get integration, we'd take 100 years if you just relied on the courts.

306
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:46,000
And we sensed that.

307
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:53,000
Can I ask you, if you will, to talk about the personal sacrifices you made at those times,

308
00:33:53,000 --> 00:34:00,000
in terms of putting yourself in harm's way, your family, the kinds of things that you experienced?

309
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:02,000
Never thought about it.

310
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:10,000
I think we were so faithful in our struggle.

311
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:15,000
And strengthened by our religious fervor.

312
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:22,000
My wife, who was sitting here with us, was assaulted by Alabama State Trooper with rifle.

313
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:26,000
And I was beaten up on Mother's Day.

314
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:31,000
I had a broken wrist and three broken ribs.

315
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:39,000
And dislocated in my back from the batons of Alabama State Highway Patrolmen.

316
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:43,000
But we never considered it.

317
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:47,000
And we never considered it a danger.

318
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:57,000
We were so committed to the idea that we were right and moral in our struggle.

319
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:00,000
That we never thought of the danger.

320
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:03,000
And of course, we had some lives lost.

321
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:11,000
And some injuries that plague us to today.

322
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:18,000
So how did you feel then at the, I mean, at the end of the Birmingham campaign?

323
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:27,000
Well, I guess the word that I learned 25 something, where we were euphoric.

324
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:35,000
Dr. King said before we went to Birmingham, if we can crack Birmingham, we can crack the south.

325
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:37,000
And that's what happened.

326
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:41,000
So afterwards, what was the next step?

327
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:44,000
Well, we'd take on anybody.

328
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:49,000
You know, we were like the heavyweight champions then.

329
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:54,000
And for you personally, what did you do after Birmingham?

330
00:35:54,000 --> 00:36:00,000
Well, I was *named* Southern Regional Coordinator for the March on Washington,

331
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:05,000
which was highly successful.

332
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:11,000
And it was an extension of our movement.

333
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:17,000
And there was nothing we couldn't do after Birmingham.

334
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:20,000
That we wouldn't try anyway.

335
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:27,000
Can you tell me a little bit about the planning for and looking back on the March on Washington?

336
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:43,000
Well, Project C, which I created at the behest [of] Dr. King's assignment, was used as an outline for the campaign in Birmingham.

337
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:55,000
And it became well, in fact, we were trying to do (likely) downtown Atlanta.

338
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:59,000
And it was the Birmingham plan.

339
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:07,000
And we were going to Danville, Virginia, which is a very mean city.

340
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:15,000
...and Dr. King *felt*.

341
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:20,000
In the wake of his assassination, maybe we wouldn't go to Danville.

342
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:28,000
So that's why Danville wasn't rescheduled.

343
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:33,000
I wonder if you could reflect how you doing up, OK, do you want to take a break?

344
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:35,000
I'm all right.

345
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:43,000
Could you reflect a little bit on the legislation that was finally achieved at the Civil Rights?

346
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:53,000
Well, we attribute to Birmingham, the Public Accommodations Act of 1964,

347
00:37:53,000 --> 00:38:04,000
and Birmingham led the Selma, and the Selma March, which led to the Voting Rights Act of 1965 too.

348
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:14,000
So two major civil rights bills were the product of our campaign in Birmingham and Selma.

349
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:22,000
And they changed the complexion of politics and economics in the South.

350
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:27,000
When those past, did you feel that you would achieve, obviously you'd achieve something,

351
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:33,000
but did you feel that you had achieved what you had set out to do or there would be more down the road?

352
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:43,000
Well, as I said, once we finished with Birmingham, we felt we could take on anybody or anything.

353
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:53,000
And it was inspirational to all of the participants in a movement.

354
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:56,000
They just wanted anything we wouldn't try.

355
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:03,000
And we were convinced that God was with us.

356
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:09,000
If he had not been for the religious infrastructure of the Black community,

357
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:13,000
we would have never achieved what we had achieved.

358
00:39:13,000 --> 00:39:17,000
Can you tell me a little bit more about that and the role of ministers?

359
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:19,000
Because I think it's very complicated.

360
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:23,000
Our As rallies were services.

361
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:32,000
And with religious songs, spirituals from 100 years,

362
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:42,000
or were cast with new lyrics, which we made into freedom songs.

363
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:54,000
So there wouldn't have been any movement in that for the African American church forces.

364
00:39:54,000 --> 00:40:02,000
Not only the people, the adults, but the young people were a part of it.

365
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:10,000
And that's why the mass rallies were so religious oriented.

366
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:21,000
It was a natural thing. It was the connection and the confederation of the Black churches

367
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:25,000
that made our movement possible.

368
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:32,000
And then King also spoke out against some of the preacher in the Big Cadillac, for example.

369
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:37,000
And then of course, the white allies who didn't come to the battle.

370
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:45,000
Well, Dr. King was critical of that type of preacher.

371
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:52,000
But it was just a passing comment and criticism.

372
00:40:52,000 --> 00:41:00,000
Most of the movement ministers were real serving priests.

373
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:12,000
Most of us were influenced by the kind of ministerial Dr. King had pursued in Birmingham.

374
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:20,000
I know that you were quite involved in typing and working with King of the letter from Birmingham jail,

375
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:24,000
which was addressed to so-called white allies.

376
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:27,000
Can you tell us a little bit about that, the press training?

377
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:39,000
Well, the interesting thing is that I was the only one in Birmingham who could make *out* Dr. King's chicken scratch writing.

378
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:46,000
And we were doing it from the edges and newspapers, from toilet paper, whatever we had.

379
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:51,000
And my secretary typed as she was exhausted.

380
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:55,000
We spent two or three nights transcribing it.

381
00:41:55,000 --> 00:41:59,000
And so I did the last part of it.

382
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:06,000
And it had become the rationale, the raison d'être of our movement.

383
00:42:06,000 --> 00:42:11,000
And the most important document of the 20th century, I believe,

384
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:20,000
is that it equals the Gettysburg address in my judgment.

385
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:22,000
I completely agree with you.

386
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:28,000
And are you able to go back to that moment in time when you're reading this chicken scratch?

387
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:34,000
You know, with a pencil stub in the margin of a newspaper and seeing these words emerge.

388
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:35,000
Can you remember them?

389
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:37,000
It came to me.

390
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:42,000
I recognized it when I was transcribing it.

391
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:45,000
That it was an unusual document.

392
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:52,000
And that put us in a mode of haste.

393
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:59,000
Because Dr. King wanted to see the copy before it went to press.

394
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:08,000
And the Religious Society of Friends, the Quakers, printed the first version of it.

395
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:11,000
And they call it tears of love.

396
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:14,000
I *told them, no, it should be called Letter from the Birmingham Jail*.

397
00:43:14,000 --> 00:43:16,000
So I named it.

398
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:24,000
And the rest is history.

399
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:32,000
The thing about the marvelous thing about it is that Dr. King had not much to work with.

400
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:35,000
Had no library, no books.

401
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:40,000
And it was what I call muscle memory from his training.

402
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:47,000
It made such an important document.

403
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:59,000
Now, when you moved on to a career in publishing, as you mentioned, briefly after that,

404
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:05,000
what led you to move out of the daily SCLC work?

405
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:11,000
Well, economics, probably.

406
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:20,000
Oh, honestly, the Board of SCLC froze my salary at $10,000 a year.

407
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:23,000
I had a wife and four children.

408
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:25,000
I couldn't make it.

409
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:33,000
And this publisher from New York, dangled $25,000 in my face and I was gone.

410
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:40,000
And I had told the Board of SCLC, I said, you look up one day and I'll be gone.

411
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:52,000
And that's where Dr. King had seen me, Rev. Martin Luther King Sr, out to my house in Atlanta to try to persuade me to stay.

412
00:44:52,000 --> 00:45:01,000
And I remember he was looking at the back window, the little stream ran through our property.

413
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:07,000
And he said, why, what are you going to do up in New York?

414
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:12,000
I told him I was going to be a marketing vice president for this publishing firm,

415
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:20,000
which was putting together a series of books about Black life in America and the world.

416
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:23,000
And he said, what are you going to pay you?

417
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:26,000
I said, were you going to start me at $25,000?

418
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:29,000
He said, were you going up there, boy?

419
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:32,000
He said, you go take care of your aunt and these babies.

420
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:39,000
And Dr. King begged me to stay, but I just, they got it.

421
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:48,000
I felt the Board of SCLC didn't, I had the responsibility of administering a million dollar budget.

422
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:55,000
And they were paying me, freezing my salary at $10,000 and I had a wife and four children.

423
00:45:55,000 --> 00:46:08,000
And I used to say that I wasn't going to let, I didn't want white folks to exploit me.

424
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:10,000
I wasn't going to let black folks do it either.

425
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:13,000
And so that's why I left.

426
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:19,000
That you remained close to King in the years when you went to New York?

427
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:20,000
Oh yes.

428
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:26,000
I remained his, I was his man in New York and representative to the UN.

429
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:30,000
And I still worked with him.

430
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:42,000
And in 1967, I was in New York as a pastor and we had a case in Birmingham for parading without a permit.

431
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:48,000
And Dr. King was absolutely committed to the nonviolent cradle.

432
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:57,000
He said, after we have exhausted our remedies, then whatever it is we do.

433
00:46:57,000 --> 00:47:00,000
So we went to jail in 1967.

434
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:09,000
And a part of the instrument was he took my picture and I took his picture in the Birmingham jail.

435
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:16,000
In fact, the picture is pretty famous although someone tried to steal credit for it.

436
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:20,000
But whoever took it had to be in jail with Dr. King.

437
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:23,000
So it's been no problem.

438
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:27,000
I now have all rights to it.

439
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:34,000
Some people use it without permission, but it's all right with me.

440
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:40,000
And you had been called, we're going to the pastor in New York.

441
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:42,000
In New York, yeah.

442
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:44,000
marvelous congregation.

443
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:52,000
When I left, you were 1800 members and 80% of them paid *tithes*.

444
00:47:52,000 --> 00:48:03,000
And the last two years I was there, we received over a million dollars just from the *tithes* and the members.

445
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:10,000
And for a church in the center of Harlem, I was thought it was fantastic.

446
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:17,000
Could *I* ask about your formal installation at the church and Dr. King was?

447
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:20,000
Yes, he was a celebrant.

448
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:25,000
He preached a sermon, not at midnight, I remember that.

449
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:38,000
And there's a picture in my room of him putting a hood on me as a symbolic of my initiation as a pastor in the church.

450
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:41,000
But it was a marvelous experience.

451
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:45,000
And his assassination came only 11 days after that.

452
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:48,000
10 days after.

453
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:54,000
Do you remember what was on his mind or talking with him during that time?

454
00:48:54,000 --> 00:49:00,000
Not really, because I was in New York and he was a Memphis.

455
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:14,000
But I always felt he was asking me to come to Memphis to organize and watch his hair for one of the marches going wrong.

456
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:23,000
And after, obviously after his death, but carrying on in the church, how did you see the movement?

457
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:30,000
If you want to call it, that playing out going forward from 1968 forward into the seventh?

458
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:42,000
Well, I felt that there was so much residual racism left in the nation, particularly cities like New York,

459
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:49,000
that the church again could be at the forefront of that movement.

460
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:57,000
And in New York, we were wrestling with the problem of quality education.

461
00:49:57,000 --> 00:50:11,000
And I became immersed in the charter school movement, which was bandied about us as well as it was good or bad and so forth.

462
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:15,000
I became a central figure in that.

463
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:29,000
In fact, Rubén Díaz Sr, Spanish, passed him in the Bronx, and I led along with Rev. Floyd H. Flake,

464
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:36,000
the struggle to get charter school legislation in the state of New York.

465
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:43,000
And I opened with a fellow named Steve Klinsky.

466
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:49,000
I opened the first charter school in New York.

467
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:55,000
I don't remember the year, but it's been ten years ago.

468
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:58,000
And it's been doing very well.

469
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:02,000
The education was a major issue.

470
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:05,000
You also mentioned drugs.

471
00:51:05,000 --> 00:51:11,000
And I know that you became very interested in South African politics, the anti-partner.

472
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:18,000
Well, parallel to my struggle in South.

473
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:24,000
Dr. King had been very vocal about apartheid movement.

474
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:39,000
I was recruited by people from the (South) African National Congress, ANC, John Stone, Mark Adini.

475
00:51:39,000 --> 00:51:50,000
And so I mobilized churches into a 300-member federation to get the truth out about apartheid.

476
00:51:50,000 --> 00:52:07,000
And I actually worked in the election of Mandela becoming president.

477
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:17,000
So I participated in two continents in the struggle against racism.

478
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:21,000
Union is out there, and the United States.

479
00:52:21,000 --> 00:52:24,000
And do you see this as all connected as a global?

480
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:27,000
Oh, yes.

481
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:30,000
hatred is a terrible disease.

482
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:40,000
And racism is the outgrowth of the hatred of one people against another, usually the downtrodden.

483
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:51,000
So it is my, I have a theological position as well as a practical political position.

484
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:58,000
Has your, talking about practical politics?

485
00:52:58,000 --> 00:52:59,000
Okay.

486
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:06,000
Yeah, if you could just expand a little bit, talk a little bit more about those positions.

487
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:19,000
Well, because I was involved in the apartheid movement, anti-apartheid movement, I got to go to South Africa several times.

488
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:28,000
And one time I took 22 ministers to be on the ground to see what apartheid was really like.

489
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:37,000
And the indigenous South African could not own land, could not live where they wanted to.

490
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:41,000
They had a carry pass books with the identity.

491
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:46,000
It was, it was a terrible form of racism.

492
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:54,000
It was systemized in the reformed church.

493
00:53:54,000 --> 00:54:00,000
And that went from that practice to legislation.

494
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:08,000
And so there was a political solution, and I joined that.

495
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:11,000
And you said you had your theological stance as well.

496
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:13,000
Can you tell us about that?

497
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:21,000
Well, the theological position is grounded in the New Testament, philosophy, and teachings of Jesus.

498
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:30,000
And I forget the gentleman who was writing a book on the making of a mind about Dr. King.

499
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:36,000
He has been, whose writing is influenced Dr. King the most.

500
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:41,000
And he said, well, who, what answers have you received?

501
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:48,000
The day to Martin Buber.

502
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:55,000
He felt it was at Walden Pond.

503
00:54:55,000 --> 00:54:57,000
Yes, [Henry David] Thoreau.

504
00:54:57,000 --> 00:55:05,000
And Paul Tillich, and they named it the folks.

505
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:12,000
The other day, I don't know, well, Dr. King was influenced by Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John.

506
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:20,000
And Andrew [Young] said, he had not received that answer from anybody.

507
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:30,000
But more than anything else, Martin Luther King was a Christian pastor.

508
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:45,000
And it was his imitation-of-Christ paradigm that a movement got its strength and its theology.

509
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:48,000
The beloved community.

510
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:49,000
Absolutely.

511
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:51,000
About that concept.

512
00:55:51,000 --> 00:56:13,000
And that comes out of the Jesus faith that black people have, and articulated by people like Martin Luther King, and Rev. Rev. Vernon Johns, and Rev. Gardner C. Taylor, and others like that.

513
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:16,000
And I continue with struggle to achieve.

514
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:19,000
Oh, absolutely.

515
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:22,000
Evil is persistent.

516
00:56:22,000 --> 00:56:27,000
And you have to fight it persistently.

517
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:40,000
And when Obama got elected, the media and the pundits began to talk about the post-racial era.

518
00:56:40,000 --> 00:56:43,000
But there is no post-racial era.

519
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:57,000
There is so much residual racism that is hardly changed for some people.

520
00:56:57,000 --> 00:57:00,000
Let me ask the room if there are any questions.

521
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:03,000
Others would like to ask at this point.

522
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:07,000
Well, I would like to use it, Martin.

523
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:10,000
I just asked a couple more questions.

524
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:14,000
You're rolling back a little bit.

525
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:16,000
But I know.

526
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:18,000
Let's do it.

527
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:20,000
We're back to the rest of the day.

528
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:29,000
I think a question about Dr. Walker, who is the failure of Memphis's campaign.

529
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:34,000
And maybe you may want to follow up to find out what those failures were.

530
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:37,000
I think Memphis are involved in it.

531
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:38,000
No, no.

532
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:47,000
In Memphis, with Walker, who is as investing the question about Dr. King, perhaps one of Dr. Walker, who comes to Memphis.

533
00:57:47,000 --> 00:57:48,000
Okay, right.

534
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:51,000
I think the failures in Memphis will be good.

535
00:57:51,000 --> 00:57:52,000
I know.

536
00:57:52,000 --> 00:57:53,000
I think we'll talk about that.

537
00:57:53,000 --> 00:57:54,000
Great.

538
00:57:54,000 --> 00:57:56,000
Any other questions?

539
00:57:56,000 --> 00:57:57,000
Okay.

540
00:57:57,000 --> 00:57:58,000
Terrific.

541
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:00,000
So just two final questions.

542
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:11,000
One is the Reverend List, alluding to something you mentioned earlier about Dr. King calling you perhaps calling you to Memphis.

543
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:13,000
Because of the difficulties of failures in Memphis.

544
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:15,000
What were the...

545
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:22,000
Well, the march that they had in Memphis was disrupted by.

546
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:24,000
I think they had a...

547
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:30,000
The name was the invaders, but they would put up to it by the FBI.

548
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:34,000
And so it couldn't be...

549
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:36,000
It had to be straightened out.

550
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:43,000
And I think that's Dr. King wanted some help with that.

551
00:58:43,000 --> 00:58:52,000
But the federal government has been complicit again and again.

552
00:58:52,000 --> 00:59:06,000
We're trying to disrupt movement in this direction, particularly the Kennedy administration.

553
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:11,000
What did you think of Dr. King's move towards jobs?

554
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:17,000
I mean, they've been there from the beginning, of course, but at that period, they're really trying to focus on the economy.

555
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:28,000
Well, that was one of the issues that grows out of the hatred that racism creates.

556
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:51,000
The lack of meaningful employment, poor schools, and not having enough burning energy to impose strict accountability.

557
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:58,000
We've seen that with the voting rights act.

558
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:05,000
There's always an attempt to dilute it, and it goes on.

559
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:08,000
So I just want to ask as a final question.

560
01:00:08,000 --> 01:00:12,000
And first, let me just again say thank you so much for your time.

561
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:16,000
And this has just been amazing to hear from you today.

562
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:18,000
We really appreciate it.

563
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:23,000
And the American public will appreciate this at this persona.

564
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:29,000
I want to ask, I know you've done many, many, many interviews like this.

565
01:00:29,000 --> 01:00:37,000
And I wonder if you ever leave those interviews thinking, oh, I wish there's one thing I just didn't get to say or one thing you didn't ask about.

566
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:42,000
No, my style is to tell the truth.

567
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:45,000
And I just do that all the time.

568
01:00:45,000 --> 01:00:52,000
My mentor, Dr. Rev. Vernon Johns, you should say that the truth is always inflammatory.

569
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:56,000
So I'm willing to do that.

570
01:00:56,000 --> 01:00:59,000
Well, we thank you for it.

571
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:02,000
You need to interview my wife.

572
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:16,000
She's the only genuine wife of one of the icons of the civil rights that exists.

573
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:22,000
And they had a book out last a long ago, a couple of years about the women of the *movement*.

574
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:26,000
And they didn't include her. It made me furious.

575
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:29,000
But she was a freedom rider.

576
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:37,000
She's been beaten with a rifle butt of Alabama State Highwayman.

577
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:47,000
And our house has been assaulted, both with guns and rocks.

578
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:53,000
In Petersburg, they shut out the lights on the parking lot.

579
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:58,000
And threw something through the front window.

580
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:02,000
And she has lived through all of that.

581
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:10,000
And been sweet and understanding and supported me, told me what to do.

582
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:18,000
The key to a long match is the husband must have the last word in his household.

583
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:21,000
Yes, dear.

584
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:26,000
Well done. Well done.

585
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:43,000
Honey, I think you were to share with them your experience on Mother's Day, 1963, before and after.

586
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:51,000
The Saturday before Mother's Day in 1963, my husband was supposed to come home for Mother's Day.

587
01:02:51,000 --> 01:03:01,000
And Dr. King asked him to stay in Birmingham because someone had bombed a King, Dr. King's brother's home.

588
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:12,000
And the people were rioting because they had gotten tired of the assaults on the black community.

589
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:19,000
My husband couldn't come home, so he asked me to bring the four children to Birmingham.

590
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:34,000
And while he was out trying to quiet the crowd, the Alabama National Guardsmen had asked us to go into the lobby of the Gaston Motel.

591
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:40,000
Two of my children were sleeping in the hotel, in the lobby, in the hotel.

592
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:45,000
And I didn't go into the lobby until I got my children.

593
01:03:45,000 --> 01:03:55,000
And I said I have two children asleep in the motel and the National Guardsman struck me in the head and sent me to the hospital.

594
01:03:55,000 --> 01:03:58,000
I said I wouldn't go to the hospital without my children.

595
01:03:58,000 --> 01:04:03,000
And we went to the hospital. And I stayed there until the next morning.

596
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:10,000
When I left the hospital, I wanted to go back to Atlanta. I was through with Birmingham.

597
01:04:10,000 --> 01:04:23,000
So the children and I went back to Atlanta. When we got to Atlanta, we were two blocks into East Point, which is where the Atlanta Airport is.

598
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:29,000
A policeman pulled up beside me and said, what do you do when you see the police sirens?

599
01:04:29,000 --> 01:04:34,000
I said you pull over. He said, well you didn't pull over, so follow me.

600
01:04:34,000 --> 01:04:52,000
I followed him to the jail. My oldest child was 11. They arrested my 11-year-old, 10-year-old, the nine-year-old, eight-year-old, and the six-year-old.

601
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:57,000
We stayed there. Well, I asked him if I could have my one phone call.

602
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:04,000
And they said, yes, I called Rev. Martin Luther King Sr, but he had left the church. And I didn't know where else to call him.

603
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:12,000
So I called Andrew Young + Jean Childs Young's wife, Gene, and told her to get in touch with Dr. King.

604
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:21,000
Oh, they told me I used my one phone call. And I said, look at my daughter, I [should also] have one phone call. And they told me, yes. So that's how I call Andrew Young + Jean Childs Young.

605
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:29,000
And Edwina, my husband's secretary, came out to the jail. And they told them we were not there.

606
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:37,000
But they had already gotten in touch with Rev. Martin Luther King Sr. And about midnight, Rev. Martin Luther King Sr came out with someone who owned his property.

607
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:47,000
Because you had to own your property outright. You couldn't have a mortgage on it. And that gentleman made bail for me.

608
01:05:47,000 --> 01:05:58,000
I had to have a trial. And they called me the day before to come to court the next day. They said, or the gentleman who had put up my bond would lose his bond.

609
01:05:58,000 --> 01:06:08,000
So I got some of the school teachers to take care of my children. And I went out to the jail to the trial. And they *fined* me $84.

610
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:15,000
And I said, well, I'm not going to pay it. So they put me in jail again. But the jail was nice and clean.

611
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:27,000
And I said, this is my chance to get a good rest. So I stayed there until my husband and Robert J. Brown were coming from Atlanta, coming through East Point.

612
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:40,000
And my husband saw my car. And he said, I know my wife is in jail out here. And Robert J. Brown came in and paid my $84.00 fine and got me out of jail.

613
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:50,000
So that's what happened in East Point, Georgia after I left Birmingham, Alabama, on Mother's Day in 1963.

614
01:06:50,000 --> 01:07:02,000
And at the same time, I wanted a motel to pick up her things. And I went out to buy my highway for a showman.

615
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:14,000
When they identified me, they began to beat me three of them. And they broke my wrist, three fractured ribs.

616
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:30,000
And they dislocated my spine with their batons. So it was a terrible weekend for us as a family.

617
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:41,000
But she's been very brave. And she went to Mississippi as a freedom rider.

618
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:57,000
I think we were the only couple that went. And she was in our cell for two people with 14 other women.

619
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:01,000
Did they play for children in jail with you or they in separate?

620
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:06,000
They just put us together.

621
01:08:06,000 --> 01:08:14,000
They figured the whole family must be *desperadoes*.

622
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:18,000
Did anything else, did you like where I was in jail with them?

623
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:28,000
Well, just to say that she's always been supportive. And I find time, or made time to write books.

624
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:38,000
And she's read all my books before I have 30 published books. And she's read all the manuscripts before they're published.

625
01:08:39,000 --> 01:08:50,000
And she's been helpful to me in my journalistic pursuits. And I now have 30 published.

626
01:08:50,000 --> 01:09:02,000
And I have about 30 more to be published. I have written 55 books at last count.

627
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:09,000
I want to say one, give you one other incident that hasn't been told.

628
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:21,000
When we lived in Petersburg and my husband was president of the Petersburg Improvement Association, he was president of CORE, he was president of SCLC.

629
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:26,000
And he was well known as an agitator.

630
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:35,000
When my daughter got ready to go to school, she was barred from all public schools because of his work in Petersburg.

631
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:40,000
There was a pupil placement form that you must sign that you would not send your child to a white school.

632
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:47,000
I didn't plan to send my child to a white school, but I didn't want to sign the pupil placement form.

633
01:09:47,000 --> 01:09:52,000
We did not sign it. So she was barred from all public schools.

634
01:09:52,000 --> 01:10:00,000
The teachers in Petersburg, who belonged to our church and some other teachers, gave me a lesson plan every evening.

635
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:09,000
And I was able to homeschool before homeschooling was popular. I homeschooled my daughter.

636
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:17,000
My daughter finished Howard University in three years. She did a *three-year* master's at Yale.

637
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:24,000
And so we are very proud of her in spite of all that Petersburg did to keep her out of school.

638
01:10:24,000 --> 01:10:31,000
She became the deputy director of the National *Endowment* for the Arts.

639
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:40,000
And she's about to retire November 1st of this year.

640
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:47,000
I want to ask one last question. And looking back over your involvement in civil rights.

641
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:52,000
Is there anything that you would have done differently?

642
01:10:53,000 --> 01:10:59,000
No, no.

643
01:10:59,000 --> 01:11:13,000
There were times when I used to think about getting vengeance revenge, but the Lord has moved that from my heart.

644
01:11:14,000 --> 01:11:22,000
And I'm not bitter. It was the time when I was very bitter, but I'm not bitter now.

645
01:11:27,000 --> 01:11:40,000
No, I just think the 60s was an exciting time to be alive. If I could have done more, I would have done more, but I had the four children, so I did what I could.

646
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:47,000
And I'm sure there are other people who know and knows about who have done much more than I did.

647
01:11:47,000 --> 01:11:54,000
I don't know how. Well, some gave their lives.

648
01:11:54,000 --> 01:12:03,000
Well, Dr. Walker, this is Walker. I can't remember. Thank you for planning this interview.

649
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:17,000
I know one of the younger people you don't know. *Maya Angelou* used to be on my staff, and she ran *our fundraising office* in New York on 25th Street.

650
01:12:17,000 --> 01:12:20,000
Great lady.

651
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:32,000
Tell the story Dr. She came to Harlem, and you and Dr. King of the dance, he said that you were in her book.

652
01:12:33,000 --> 01:12:39,000
I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings.

653
01:12:39,000 --> 01:12:49,000
Someone told me a thread, Wilkinson was the first one to go on the show. She went to a rally at Manalovian Church, and saw me with Dr. King at it.

654
01:12:49,000 --> 01:12:55,000
I was too young for wisdom and too handsome for virtue.

655
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:09,000
Wow, that sounds like it.

656
01:13:09,000 --> 01:13:10,000
Thank you.

657
01:13:10,000 --> 01:13:19,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
